snippet: Payrolls in the United States grew by 113,000 in January, a weaker-than-expected increase that experts said may signal a loss of momentum in the economy. The unemployment rate dipped to 6.6 percent.
abstract: Government reports that payrolls in United States grew by 113,000 in January 2014, weaker-than-expected increase that experts say may signal loss of momentum in economy; unemployment rate dipped to 6.6 percent, its lowest level since October 2008.
lead_paragraph: Payrolls in the United States grew by 113,000 in January, a weaker-than-expected increase that experts said may signal a loss of momentum in the economy. The unemployment rate dipped to 6.6 percent.

headline.main: Payroll Data Shows a Lag in Wages, Not Just Hiring
